Ensure 2.x changes are backwards compatible.

These changes make the 2.x branch compatible with maven-compiler-plugin 2.x.  maven-compiler-plugin 3.x must make changes to AbstractCompilerMojo to call both variants of the compile method.  Eg, something like this:

		CompilerResult compilerResult;
        try
        {
            try 
            {
               compilerResult = compiler.performCompile( compilerConfiguration );
            } 
            catch (CompilerNotImplementedException cnie) 
            {
                messages = compiler.compile( compilerConfiguration );
				compilerResult = makeCompilerResult(messages);
            }
        }
        catch ( Exception e )
        {
            // TODO: don't catch Exception
            throw new MojoExecutionException( "Fatal error compiling", e );
        }

I renamed the new compile method to performCompile, but I am not too happy with the name. Perhaps you can find a better one.

issue_comments.body:
The root of the problem seems to be in `EclipseJavaCompiler.isPackage`. It tests if a potential package name begins with an uppercase letter and returns false if so:

```
if ( Character.isUpperCase( packageName[0] ) )
{
    return false;
}
```

So apparently the code assumes a package name can never start with an uppercase letter? I tried just removing that check. But that created other issues because the code assumes that for any other identifier, it is a package as long as there doesn't exist a `some/package/name.java` or `some/package/name.class` file corresponding to the identifier. So the `WrongClassname` test fails because it thinks `org.codehaus.foo.RightClassname` is a package name (the only thing keeping it from being recognized as a package in the past was the fact that it started with an upper case letter).
